n the chemical industry doing research on products or in the environment and studying how certain chemicals affect the environment. I am also very interested in working in the medical field, and how certain chemicals affect biological systems or bodies. I want to go to medical school in addition to exploring the field of research. ','This experience can benefit me by helping me develop and define my skills in leadership, communication, teamwork and skills in the laboratory. I am also hoping to learn what it is like to work in the scientific discipline, and gain more experience in research. ','Yes, I can commit to the 10 week program. '),(19,'Victoria Natalie Haro','vharo3','54 E Chalmers St. Apt. 504A','Champaign, Il 61820 ','Sophmore','3.63','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/vharo3/new resume.docx',NULL,'vharo3@illinois.edu','8579 W 73rd Pl. ','Justice, Il 60458','3129250095','IB 150- Organismal & Evolutionary Biology\r\nMCB 150- Molec & Cellular Basis of Life\r\nIB 204- Genetics\r\nIB 202- Anatomy and physiology\r\nIB 302- Evolution\r\nAlso participated in many merit classes for these biology courses. \r\n\r\n','4','1','8','7','2','6','5','3','I am debating between either going into the health field under pediatrics or to do research in anatomy and physiology or Evolutionary Developmental Biology. I worked under Karen Sears last semester and found her work very interesting. Here is the first time I began to think of research as a career goal. Not only research in general but research in Mammalian Evolutionary Developmental Biology. Working in her lab opened my eyes to how life changing and relevant the research we perform really is. In labs that I had taken for class it was a little different because I would just follow the procedures and learn what they wanted me to learn. Actually doing research you get to come across new findings, even ones you didn\'t think you come across. ','This experience would befitting to me because the more exposure I get the more I can decide if this is the future I want to pursue. If so this experience can also help me figure out what research I want to do specifically. It would also give me many skills that I will be using in my future career. Even if research is not what I decide to go into, this experience would still be very beneficial. These are still skills that I will use in my future. It also helps you look at the science in a different angle and encourages me to question the information in my textbook, not just accept it. Its also befitting to me because I love to work as a team and am very dedicated to something that I begin. I am also very enthusiastic about performing research at this moment in my life. ','Yes, I planned to stay in Champaign this summer but did not want to waste it. This would be a perfect way for me to spend my summer. I am not only am gaining knowledge but also experience in my major. '),(21,'Michael Trevino','mtrevin2','202 E. Peabody','Champaign, IL 60462','Freshman','3.14','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/mtrevin2/Resume- Michael Trevino.pdf',NULL,'mtrevin2@illinois.edu','14033 Terry Drive','Orland Park, IL 60462','708-620-9778','  I have taken Molecular and Cellular Biology 150 and am currently enrolled in Integrative Biology 150.  I have found both classes fascinating in their own respects. In Molecular and Cellular Biology the topic of viruses in reference to HIV gave me insight about a real world application of disease and the complex research that is conducted to alleviate it. At the same time, within Integrative Biology, I enjoy the larger scope of life and the interwoven challenges organisms face, and the diversity that arises when those challenges are unraveled.\r\n','1','2','5','6','4','3','8','7','   My career goals lie in what I am passionate about, service. Amongst all else, this core value must, and will, remain centric. However, the form in which this service manifests itself calls me to two fields within science. I have a dream to become a physician, and have the opportunity to interact and assist in the recovery of patients every single day. Yet another part of me is drawn to research, where my service wouldn’t be to a select group of patients, but instead could possibly impact millions of people globally on an immense scale. Having the opportunity to contribute creative solutions to an ever-changing set of obstacles is extremely enticing.','  Research is an opportunity characterized by real world relevance. I see this experience as a chance to gain perspective on science outside of a classroom.  Insight into techniques and resources used inside a legitimate lab would be an excellent chance to gain hands-on experience. Not only that, but having the opportunity to work with a faculty mentor would be extremely valuable. Collaborating and learning from someone who has a genuine enthusiasm for their craft would only seek to inspire and inform me. Lastly, and most importantly, this experience would benefit me by giving me an opportunity to do what I love; learn. New information is empowering and I want to be part of a generation that has the drive to pursue it.\r\n','  I can absolutely dedicate myself to the time requirements of the program. '),(22,'Nmerichi Nwakanma','nwakanm2','1115 W. Nevada St.','Urbana, IL 61801','Junior','3.53','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/nwakanm2/MY OFFICIAL RESUME.docx',NULL,'nwakanm2@illinois.edu','150 Ash St.','Park Forest, IL 60466','7087330880','Integrative Biology 150\r\nIntegrative Biology 151 (lab)\r\nMolecular and Cellular Biology 150\r\nMicrobial lab 101\r\nIntroduction to microbiology 100\r\nMolecular and Cellular Biology 250 (molecular and cellular genetics)\r\nMolecular and Cellular Biology Lab 251\r\nHuman Anatomy and Physiology 244\r\nHuman Anatomy and Physiology 245 (lab)\r\nHuman Anatomy and Physiology 246\r\nHuman Anatomy and Physiology 247 (lab)\r\n','5','1','6','2','3','8','7','4','Everything about biology interests me. I find it rather interesting to be educated and have a basic knowledge about biology from how we evolved from Apes to how the human body operates. My ultimate career goal is to become a physician and also be involved in a cutting edge, state of the art research that focuses on using environmental biological research and stem cell research to find medical cures and answers to diseases that are still mysterious to science.','This experience is something that I\'ve been praying and searching for because of the fact that it\'ll help me diversify and expand my knowledge in biology. As a molecular and cellular biology major, the opportunity to gain knowledge about environmental biology is quite limited for me during the school year because MCB courses takes up my schedule. With this research opportunity, not only will I get to work and learn from a professor who\'s an expert in his/her field, but I\'ll also be able to be immerse myself and my summer into learning more about environmental biology. That way, I\'ll have the resources to be able to continue my research in environmental biology throughout the school year','Yes, I am more than willing and excited to commit to the time requirements of this program if given the opportunity to do so.'),(23,'Catherine C Cantoran','cantorn2','1111 West Nevada','Urbana, IL','Freshman','3.0','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/cantorn2/Resume.docx',NULL,'cathycantoran@live.com','216 Burlington ave','Westmont, IL','6302012690','By the end of this semester, I will have completed Integrative Biology 150 and Molecular and Cellular Biology 150.','7','1','8','4','5','3','6','2','My main goal is to graduate the University of Illinois with a degree in biology, and then apply to Veterinary school and become a veterinarian for small mammals. Since I can remember I\'ve always wanted to become a veterinarian and interested in animals. But since I have been at the University of Illinois, I have also grown a desire for general medicine and human immunology.  My experience as an Emergency Medical Responder has really nurtured a thirst and love for helping others and unscrambling the human body. My goals and current efforts are still geared toward animals and biology but my ultimate dream would be to incorporate the two and bring the biology to a full circle and maybe even work for the FDA or USDA. ','I know this experience will benefit me in more than one way. I think this experience will not only give me practical experience in a lab but also life direction. As I previously stated, I do have an intended direction but hope to incorporate more to it. This fellowship will give me more experience and more insight on the road ahead of me.  I am also curious to understand environmental and ecological relationships of nature and animals; I believe that this is crucial in order to have a full understanding of biology. This fellowship will foster my curiosity, and give me the opportunity to work with professionals with the same passion. My general path is to receive a degree in biology, therefore this fellowship will undoubtedly benefit my understanding of biology and labs.','Yes, if I am accepted for this fellowship I will make this my main priority and schedule around. '),(24,'Alexis C. Williams','acwilli2','1002 W. College CT','Urbana IL, 61801','Freshman','3.4','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/acwilli2/Alexis Resume.docx',NULL,'acwilli2@illinois.edu','5355 W. Potomac','Chicago IL, 60651','7736775425','I have not taken any biology courses yet.','8','7','3','2','6','4','5','1','At this moment, I\'m a undeclared freshman but, as far as my career goals I would like to major in Kinesiology. In the future I would like to become a Physical Therapist or Athletic Trainer. As far as school goals, I want to participate in different types of research studies. Many people around the University of Illinois campus said that participating in research studies is fun and you learn a lot. So with that being, I thought I should start early with participating in research studies and to see for myself how fun it could be.','This experience will benefit me because I\'am a person who likes to try new things especially when its positive, help me gain new information,and dealing with the community. Before coming to this University, people that graduated from this school always told me that participating in research studies is the one thing that I have to do throughout my four years at the University of Illinois. They never told me the exact reason why, but they did say I wont regret committing my time. From that day on I was open to participating in research studies. At the end of the process I believe i will gain a lot of information, meet new people, and also do something positive that\'s associated with my school.','Yes I can commit the time requirements for the 10 week program.'),(25,'Alexis C.Williams','acwilli2','1002 W College Ct','Urbana IL, 61801','Freshman','3.4','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/acwilli2/image.jpg',NULL,'acwilli2@illinois.edu','5355 W Potomac ','Chicago IL, 60651','7736775425','I have not taken any biology courses yet.','8','7','3','2','6','4','5','1','At this moment, I\'m an undeclared freshman but as far as my career goals I would like to major in kinesiology. In the future I would like to become a physical therapist or athletic trainer. As far as school goals, I want to participate in different types of research studies. Many people around the University if Illinois campus said that participating in research studies is fun and you learn a lot. So with that being said , I though I should start early with participating in research studies and to see for myself how fun it could be.\r\n','This experience will benefit me because I\'am a person who likes to try new things especially when it\'s positive, help me gain new information, and dealing with the community. Before coming to this university, people I knew who graduated prior to me attending this school to me that participating in research studies is the one thing that I have to do before my four years are up. They never told me the exact reason why, but did say it was worth commuting my time. From that day on I was open to participating in research studies. At the end of the process I believe I will gain a lot of information, meet new people, and also do something positive that\'s associated with the community and my school.','Yes I can commit the time requirements for the 10 week program\r\n'),(26,'Alexis C. Williams','acwilli2','1002 W. College CT','Urbana IL, 61801','Freshman','3.4','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/acwilli2/Alexis Resume.docx',NULL,'acwilli2@illinois.edu','5355 W. Potomac','Chicago IL, 60651','7736775425','I have not taken any biology courses yet.','8','7','3','2','6','4','5','1','At this moment, I\'m a undeclared freshman but, as far as my career goals I would like to major in Kinesiology. In the future I would like to become a Physical Therapist or Athletic Trainer. As far as school goals, I want to participate in different types of research studies. Many people around the University of Illinois campus said that participating in research studies is fun and you learn a lot. So with that being, I thought I should start early with participating in research studies and to see for myself how fun it could be.','This experience will benefit me because I\'am a person who likes to try new things especially when its positive, help me gain new information,and dealing with the community. Before coming to this University, people that graduated from this school always told me that participating in research studies is the one thing that I have to do throughout my four years at the University of Illinois. They never told me the exact reason why, but they did say I wont regret committing my time. From that day on I was open to participating in research studies. At the end of the process I believe i will gain a lot of information, meet new people, and also do something positive that\'s associated with my school.','Yes I can commit the time requirements for the 10 week program.'),(27,'Viridiana Luna ','vluna6','107 E Springfield Apt 206','Champaign Illinois','Freshman','3.94 ','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/vluna6/Resume.docx',NULL,'vluna6@illinois.edu ','2736 West 43rd Street','Chicago Ilinois','773-964-2757 ','I am a Molecular and Cellular Biology major. The biology courses I have completed include MCB 150 Molecular and Cellular Basis of Life, IB 150 Organismal and Evolutionary Biology, MCB 250 Molecular Genetics, and MCB 251 Experimental Techniques in Molecular Biology. I am currently enrolled in MCB 252 Cells, Tissue, and Development, and MCB 253 Experimental Techniques in Cell Biology. Additionally, I am receiving credit for MCB 290 Undergraduate Research. I am an undergraduate research assistant for Dr. Megan Dailey of the Animal Science Department. ','6','1','8','3','2','5','7','4','Initially, my goal was to acquire a MD degree and become a physician. After being an undergraduate research assistant at Dr. Dailey’s Lab and learning more about biological research, I am considering pursuing a MD/PhD dual degree. The area of medicine in which I would most like to base my career around is gynecology and women’s health. After receiving my MD/PhD degree, I want to complete a residency program in gynecology. I aspire to become a gynecologist because, being a women of color, I understand the necessity of providing health services for women in communities that often go under-served. The College of Medicine at UIC is my top choice of medical schools. I enjoy learning about mammalian evolution, genetic disorders, and the anatomy and physiology of animals.','Becoming a recipient of this summer research fellowship will give me the chance to expand my knowledge in a field, animal biology, that I want to be more familiar with. I have much to learn as an undergraduate, therefore, opportunities like these are essential regardless of which career path I choose to take. I believe that in order for me to one day be accepted into medical or graduate school, I need to have role models and mentors that can guide me. I deem it important to make connections with people who have already been successful in field of biological research. I want to build my research skills further outside of the MCB curriculum. I think this program will give me a holistic perspective of biological research to translate into my future endeavors in research.  ','Yes, I can commit to the time requirements of the 10 week program. I would not have an issue with living in Champaign this summer and find housing. I do not intend on taking any summer classes to be able to dedicate my time to this research fellowship. During this semester, I\'ve managed being a full time student as well as working part time and doing research in Dr. Dailey’s lab. I believe I will be able to manage my time well with this program. '),(28,'Viridiana Luna','vluna6','107 E Springfield Apt 206','Champaign Illinois','Sophmore','3.94 ','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/vluna6/Resume.docx',NULL,'vluna6@illinois.edu ','2736 West 43rd Street','Chicago Ilinois','7739642757','I am a Molecular and Cellular Biology major. The biology courses I have completed include MCB 150 Molecular and Cellular Basis of Life, IB 150 Organismal and Evolutionary Biology, MCB 250 Molecular Genetics, and MCB 251 Experimental Techniques in Molecular Biology. I am currently enrolled in MCB 252 Cells, Tissue, and Development, and MCB 253 Experimental Techniques in Cell Biology. Additionally, I am receiving credit for MCB 290 Undergraduate Research. I am an undergraduate research assistant for Dr. Megan Dailey of the Animal Science Department.','6','1','8','3','2','5','7','4','Initially, my goal was to acquire a MD degree and become a physician. After being an undergraduate research assistant at Dr. Dailey’s Lab and learning more about biological research, I am considering pursuing a MD/PhD dual degree. The area of medicine in which I would most like to base my career around is gynecology and women’s health. After receiving my MD/PhD degree, I want to complete a residency program in gynecology. I aspire to become a gynecologist because, being a women of color, I understand the necessity of providing health services for women in communities that often go under-served. The College of Medicine at UIC is my top choice of medical schools. I enjoy learning about mammalian evolution, genetic disorders, and the anatomy and physiology of animals.','Becoming a recipient of this summer research fellowship will give me the chance to expand my knowledge in a field, animal biology, that I want to be more familiar with. I have much to learn as an undergraduate, therefore, opportunities like these are essential regardless of which career path I choose to take. I believe that in order for me to one day be accepted into medical or graduate school, I need to have role models and mentors that can guide me. I deem it important to make connections with people who have already been successful in field of biological research. I want to build my research skills further outside of the MCB curriculum. I think this program will give me a holistic perspective of biological research to translate into my future endeavors in research.','Yes, I can commit to the time requirements of the 10 week program. I would not have an issue with living in Champaign this summer and find housing. I do not intend on taking any summer classes to be able to dedicate my time to this research fellowship. During this semester, I\'ve managed being a full time student as well as working part time and doing research in Dr. Dailey’s lab. I believe I will be able to manage my time well with this program.'),(29,'Maria Cardona','mvcardo2','1005 W Gregory Dr','Urbana, IL 61801','Freshman','3.3','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/mvcardo2/Maria Cardona-Resume.docx',NULL,'mvcardo2@illinois.edu','5469 N New England','Chicago, IL 60656','7737067691','I have currently completed IB 150 and have enjoyed the experience with my favorite assignment of the semester being the group Wiki project. This project had us do research on a topic of a certain biological problem, create our own solution to the problem and then present the information we had found to the class. This course gave a good basis of information about evolutionary development, biological diversity and genetic diversity to name some topics.\r\nThis semester I am taking MCB 150 which is different in that it has dove straight into a lot of content very quickly. MCB, as opposed to IB, focuses more on the in depth information about what is occurring in the cells of Eukaryotes, Prokaryotes, and Achaea and how that affects life forms.','2','4','8','5','6','7','3','1','My career goals are to complete college in four years with degrees in MCB and Psych with a possible minor in IB, apply to med school and attend, then complete residency to become a neurosurgeon or delve into research in neuroscience. Some of my scientific interests include neurobiology, genetics, sensory processing, mind perception, DNA biology, and evolutionary development.','Being accepted into this summer program allows me to put my time to good use, so I am able to fully invest myself into any research I will be doing, rather than try to balance school work and research. This opportunity is ideal for me because research is essential to my goals and this will better prepare me for the workload I will be facing in the future. Furthermore, I can learn from my mentor’s processes and my peers, which are valuable resources. I know this program could quench my thirst for discovering new things; in all the professors there was at least one thing about them that had interested me. This experience befits my passion for science and knowledge, but to be able to complete it with my peers and mentor makes it much more worthwhile and exciting.','Yes I am able to commit to the time requirements, this program would become the basis to my future 2014 summer plans. In other words, if accepted, all other plans for summer will be dropped or shaped in order to be able to participate in this opportunity.'),(30,'Hei Yu Chan','heichan2','918 West Illinois Street','Townsend 380','Freshman','4.00','app/views/static/Forms/ABSRF/heichan2/Hei Chan_resume.doc',NULL,'heichan2@illinois.edu','748 W 30TH ST','Chicago, IL 60616','3125903153','I took IB 150 last semester, which provided me with a solid foundation of physiology and anatomy, genetics, and evolution, and I\'m currently learning about the different biological mechanisms that take place in the molecular level in MCB 150.','6','3','5','4','1','2','7','8','I spent much of my childhood solving puzzles, which fueled in me a passion for problem-solving. My 2012 internship at Loyola University Chicago is most indicative of this. I performed research on nitrile hydratase enzyme from PtNHase, in which findings from the project could eventually lead to a more eco-friendly means of producing plastic. This experience left me in awe of the problem-solving potential of research. Completion of IB 150 affirmed my decision to become a biological researcher, as I found it intriguing to study how environmental factors affect species. I am especially interested in looking at how man-induced environmental changes affect the physiology and genetics of living organisms, with the ultimate goal to preserve and enhance current biodiversity. ','I think the AAP animal biology summer fellowship will serve as a bridge to my dream of becoming a biological researcher. Participation in this program will allow me to gain hands-on experience in the techniques used in a laboratory, while also allowing me to apply and expand upon what I have learned in class. I have only conducted research in the context of biochemistry, so I am really excited about the possibility of engaging in research involving animals and plants. In addition, this fellowship will expose me to many fields in Biology so as to better understand my own research interests and allow me to network with people who share my passion.','Yes, I will be able to commit to the time requirements.');
